[See https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5384584,186 for a map of Australia showing the location of New South Wales.

The following is excerpted from R Coombes. Europe steps up action against vaccine hesitancy as measles outbreaks continue BMJ 2017; 359:j4803 doi: https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.j4803 (Published 16 October 2017):

As measles outbreaks continue to occur in Europe as a result of growing "vaccine hesitancy," countries are exploring best approaches to counteracting parental concerns over safety. The Director of the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control, "Andrea Ammon, said that governments and doctors need to engage head on with parents over safety concerns. She praised Denmark, where rates of human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccination have plummeted, for taking its message to social media in a campaign that is showing some early promise."

"Ammon said that mandatory vaccination policies were not necessarily the answer across Europe. 'People are watching what happens in France very closely. These changes have to be done in the context of the country, and it won't suit everyone.' Instead, she said that health authorities had to be prepared to be creative.

"We have to get out of our comfort zone and do something new. We may have to change our approach; we have so far focused on evidence in a transparent way, but we may have to think about how to add an emotional component," she said.

"Denmark has drawn praise for responding dynamically to people's concerns over HPV vaccination. Working with the Danish Medical Association and the Danish Cancer Society, the national health authority has signed up a network of doctors to take part in a campaign on Facebook, where they respond individually to parents who post concerns on the platform."

"The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control has issued a guide for healthcare workers to aid communication with parents and patients over vaccine decisions (https://ecdc.europa.eu/en/immunisation-vaccines/childhood-vaccination/lets-talk-about)."

[This guide is aimed to help parents understand the importance of vaccination. Of course, some parents are not open to discussion, thus the healthcare community must find new creative ways to reach these individuals. - Mod.LK]

Additional suggested reading:
Moberly T. UK doctors re-examine case for mandatory vaccination BMJ 2017; 358:j3414 doi: https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.j3414 (Published 18 Jul 2017).

